# A debounce function to limit the rate at which a function is called

```javascript
function debounce(func, delay) {
  let timeoutId;
  return function(...args) {
    clearTimeout(timeoutId);
    timeoutId = setTimeout(() => {
      func.apply(this, args);
    }, delay);
  };
}

// Example: search input that performs API requests only after 300ms of inactivity
const searchInput = document.querySelector('#search-input');

function performSearch(query) {
  console.log(`Searching for: ${query}`);
  // In a real app, you'd make an API call here
}

const debouncedSearch = debounce(performSearch, 300);

searchInput.addEventListener('input', (event) => {
  debouncedSearch(event.target.value);
});
```

The function `debounce` delays the execution of a function until after a specified time has elapsed since the last time it was called, ensuring the inner function isn't invoked too frequently.
